    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-07-25T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-07-25T04:00:00-05:00" n="151"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d151">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1222: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-07-25T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 25, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 25—6:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>614. Legation’s 613, July 25, 11 a.m.<note n="61" xml:id="d151fn61">Not
                        printed.</note> Following from American Consul at Foochow: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“July 24, 11 a.m. Returned to Foochow 11 p.m., July 24th, with all
                            Americans in Lu territory except: at Chungan, Messrs. Cassidy and Grace
                            who are in area now surrounded by local Communists (Lu personally
                            assured me he would escort them to a place of safety at first <pb
                                facs="0248" n="150" xml:id="pg_150"/> opportunity. I do not believe
                            he will as he is concentrating all his forces for another attack on
                            Foochow.); at Kienningfu, Curran and Werner who are remaining to assist
                            Cassidy and Grace; at Shaowu, Doctors Bliss and Judd who consider it
                            safer to remain there than try to come out through bandit-infested
                            areas; at Yenping, Dr. Skinner and wife who could not leave as his
                            hospital is crowded with wounded soldiers, Miss Glamour Burner [<hi
                                rend="italic">Glassburner</hi>] who refused to leave; at Lekdu near
                            Mintsing, Dr. Ruth Herway [<hi rend="italic">Hemenway</hi>] too ill to
                            travel. Yenping and Mintsing in no immediate danger. All other Americans
                            now safe at Foochow.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
